<h4 id="why-vector-space-">Why vector space ?</h4>
<p>We are pretty familiar with 2-dimensional and 3-dimensional vector space, and
how about 4-dimensional vector space, such as spacetime.  we want to generalize
this, so vector space comes.</p>

<h4 id="terminology">Terminology</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Linear Algebra: the study of vector space is also called linear algebra.</li>
  <li>Scalar: \(\overrightarrow{v}=(v_{1},v_{2},\cdots,v_{n})\) and
\(\overrightarrow{v}=(c \cdot v_{1},c \cdot v_{2},\cdots,c \cdot v_{n})\),
and c is called a scalar</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="vector-space-properties">Vector Space Properties</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Addition \(\overrightarrow{v}\), \(\overrightarrow{w}\) are vectors, \(\overrightarrow{v} +  \overrightarrow{w}\) also a vector.</li>
  <li>Commutativity: \(\overrightarrow{v} +  \overrightarrow{w} = \overrightarrow{w} +  \overrightarrow{v}\)</li>
  <li>Identity element: \(0+  \overrightarrow{v} = \overrightarrow{v} +  0\)</li>
  <li>Inverses: \(\overrightarrow{v} +  \overrightarrow{-v} = \overrightarrow{-v} +  \overrightarrow{v} = 0\)</li>
  <li>Associativity: (\(\overrightarrow{v} +  \overrightarrow{w}) + \overrightarrow{z}= \overrightarrow{v} +  (\overrightarrow{w}+\overrightarrow{z})\)</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="scalars-properties">Scalars Properties</h4>
<ol>
  <li>distributive properties: \(c \cdot (\overrightarrow{v}+\overrightarrow{w}) = c \cdot \overrightarrow{v} + c \cdot{\overrightarrow{w}}\)</li>
  <li>associative properties:</li>
</ol>

<p>So vector space are commutative groups</p>

