   \(V =a_{5} x^{5}+a_{4} x^{4}+a_{3} x^{3}+a_{2} x^{2}+a_{1} x+a_{0}\)</p>
  </li>
  <li>\(V ={f(x)| \text { f is continuous on R}}\)
    <h4 id="relationship-between-linear-algebra-and-others-math-branches">Relationship Between Linear Algebra and Others Math Branches</h4>
  </li>
  <li>Linear algebra is central to almost all aeras of mathmatics.</li>
  <li>Linear algebra is fundamental in modern presentations of geometry, including
for defining basic objects such as lines, planes and rotations.</li>
  <li>Functional Analysis may be basicaly viewed as the application of linear
algebra to space of functions.</li>
  <li>most textbooks, introduce geometric space from linear algebra, and geometry
is often presented at elementary level, as a subfield of linear algebra</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="basis-of-vector-spacelinear-space">Basis of Vector Space(Linear Space)</h4>
<p>An (ordered) basis of a linear space $W$, is an ordered list 
$B=[\vec{w_1},\vec{w_2},\cdots,\vec{w_n}]$ of elements of W with the properties:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Spanning set: every $w \in W$ can be written:
\(w=a_{1} \vec{w}_{1}+a_{2} \vec{w}_{2}+\dots+a_{n} \vec{w}_{n}\)</li>
  <li>Linear independent
\(a_{1} \vec{w}_{1}+a_{2} \vec{w}_{2}+\dots+a_{n} \vec{w}_{n}=\vec{0}\) $\rightarrow a_1=a_2=\cdots=a_n=0$</li>
</ol>

<h5 id="examples-1">Examples 1</h5>
<p>$W=V^n$ where <br />
\(B=\left[e_{1}, e_{2}, \cdots, e_{n}\right]\) <br />
\(e_{i}=\left(\begin{array}{l}{0} \\ {0} \\ {\vdots} \\ {1} \\
{0}\end{array}\right)\)</p>

<h5 id="examples-2">Examples 2</h5>
<p>$W=P^3$ where <br />
\(B=\left[1, \alpha, \alpha^{2}, \alpha^{3}\right]\)</p>

